---

# Motion Design Principles

Motion should:
- feel physically believable
- feel emotionally aligned
- preserve orientation
- preserve continuity
- remain readable
- stay restrained

Avoid:
- random motion
- decorative movement
- constant floating
- animation spam
- exaggerated bounces
- conflicting motion systems
- motion for its own sake

The best animation often feels:
inevitable.

---

# Transition Synchronization Rules

All animated layers must remain synchronized.

Review:
- safe-area backgrounds
- page backgrounds
- report card backgrounds
- overlays
- gradients
- blur layers
- navigation wrappers
- shared surfaces

Detect:
- desynced transitions
- safe-area changing earlier
- delayed card background updates
- independent timing systems
- mismatched easing curves
- inconsistent animation duration

The user should perceive:
one unified surface transitioning together.

---

